##Finding patient zero: The mystery of the Singapore meeting that triggered the five-nation spread of the new coronavirus

From January 20 to 22,109 employees from around the world gathered in Grand Hyatt Hong Kong for an internal meeting at UK gas analysis instruments company SERVOMEX.

During this period, a lion dance troupe of Eight people went to the venue to entertain and performed for about 5 minutes.

Just over a week after the regular meeting, a Malaysian employee who attended the meeting was diagnosed with COVID-19. The man's sister and mother-in-law were also infected.

Two South Korean staff members who dined with the man were later confirmed to have been infected; four Singaporean staff members also developed symptoms, and three of them were confirmed.

The most well-known case of infection so far is that of Steve Walsh, a British employee who attended the meeting. Walsh left Singapore for a ski resort in France before flying back to Britain from Geneva. After returning to the UK, he took yoga classes in the local community and went to a pub.

Eventually, Walsh was diagnosed and infected 11 more people in Britain, France and Spain.

The Singapore government and the World Health Organization are investigating the Hyatt Hotel meeting, the Lianhe Zaobao and Reuters reported Feb. 13. But so far, there is still a key question unresolved: Who is the "patient zero" of the international epidemic.

Investigators say it is important to find patient zero, because the chain of infection can only be determined if the source of the infection is found.

Of the 109 employees who attended the January meeting, only 15 were local Singaporeans, while the remaining 94 were from China, Malaysia, South Korea, the US, Japan and European countries. All 94 had left Singapore after the meeting.

There had been a seemingly clear clue that one of the Chinese employees at the meeting was from Wuhan, Hubei Province.

But none of the more than a dozen Chinese employees at the meeting were confirmed to have the disease, according to a spokeswoman for the company. The incubation period after COVID-19 infection is about 14 days, and it's now more than 14 days since the meeting.

As of Feb. 13, seven of the employees who had attended the meeting had been diagnosed, according to the World Health Organization Organization. There are three in Singapore, two in South Korea, one in the UK and one in Malaysia, with no Chinese staff.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: World Health Organization

After the initial trail went cold, the movements of employees other than the Chinese in Singapore became the focus of attention.

The first confirmed Malaysian employee arrived in Singapore on Jan. 16, well before the meeting, according to the Ministry of Health. The employee has visited Gardens by the Bay and dined in shopping malls such as Clarke Quay and Orchard Road.

The two South Korean employees also arrived in Singapore two days early on January 18. One of the South Korean employees also dined with a Malaysian employee.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo: Lianhe Zaobao

At the same time, the opening day of the conference to the scene of the lion dance team and the Grand Hyatt Hotel also became the object of attention.

According to the head of the Lion Dance Troupe, the show lasted only about five minutes. Drummers were outside the venue, and those who entered were wearing lion heads and bodies. They did not have direct contact with the participants, nor did they eat with them.

The head of the delegation said in an interview on February 7 that the members of the group who performed on January 20 have so far shown no symptoms. But just in case, they will have a medical examination later.

The Grand Hyatt said none of its employees were currently showing symptoms of COVID-19. Staff and contractors entering and leaving the hotel take temperature measurements every day.

After the January meeting, officials said, the hotel had been thoroughly cleaned and a special agency had been hired to thoroughly disinfect rooms that might have been affected. And until now, the hotel still does not know exactly how, where and when the attendees were infected.

WHO believes that it is too early to determine whether the Grand Hyatt incident constitutes a "super-transmission event. ".

Dale Fisher, president of World Health Organization's global outbreak and Alert Response Network, acknowledged that the inability to identify the source of the infection "does make us uneasy" and that not knowing where it originated would make prevention and control measures less effective.

Paul Tambyah, an expert on infectious diseases at the National University of Singapore, speculates that the source of infection may be someone other than the attendees. "everyone thinks it's the attendees, but it could also be the cleaners, the waiters, and others. ".

Gan Kim Yong, the head of the Ministry of Health, has said authorities will continue to track down "patient zero" until the outbreak is over.

But with the passage of time, tracing will become more and more difficult. Another result, Gan Kim Yong admits, is that "we may never find patient zero. ".
